context than just my current role because I feel like there's a lot of different things I

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:38.079
messed around with. So for example, right now I think a large amount of what we do, and I think

00:07:38.079 --> 00:07:44.239
this is true generally of like tech versus finance, is we spend a lot of time looking at

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:52.239
user activity and user behavior. A lot of big tech firms, YouTube, Google,

00:07:52.959 --> 00:07:59.040
you know, Facebook, all of these firms, they have a lot of users. And so I think the broad

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:04.640
categories I would break that down into is there's a lot of need to just understand, right? There's

00:08:04.640 --> 00:08:11.519
just like, let's just do, I call it like EDA on steroids, right? Let's just understand what's

00:08:11.519 --> 00:08:16.320
happening. And I think one of the things I kind of tell people is like, this is like the ultimate,

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:21.760
there's like a data science dilemma that happens all the time, which is like you are in a job where

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:25.359
you complain about how much you don't, you don't have enough data. You're like, oh my, I wish I had

00:08:25.359 --> 00:08:29.600
more data. And then like you're in a job where you have like too much data, like, oh my God,

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:33.359
there's so much data. So there's always this like tension between too much and too little. And I

00:08:33.359 --> 00:08:41.280
think one of the patterns I would say is like, we spend a lot of time, I think, making sense of

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:46.000
really, really large data sets in a variety of ways, right? Either through really good EDA,

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:51.919
actually making good charts and like aggregating data is like a skill that I think is really

00:08:51.919 --> 00:08:58.080
valuable. And then we spend a lot of time doing, I think, a blend of sort of experiment analysis.

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:05.200
There's big tech firms run experiments and causal inference, right? So you often want

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:09.280
to understand that this is just a correlation or there's actually some causation to it.

00:09:10.239 --> 00:09:17.679
And then sort of going back a little bit further, like in finance, I think it's very much about

00:09:17.679 --> 00:09:23.280
understanding what's going on in markets versus, it's like people versus markets, right? There's a

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:28.239
lot about like understanding what's going on in markets. You don't get to run experiments. You

00:09:28.239 --> 00:09:34.479
have to basically rely on observational data. You have to like sort of wonder like, did this event

00:09:34.559 --> 00:09:39.760
actually cause the market to move or was it something else? You try to understand risk and

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:44.000
you tend to build like risk models and you tend to sort of think about that. But again, the common

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:49.359
thing there is you often just have a lot of data, a lot of market data, and you kind of make sense

00:09:49.359 --> 00:09:55.039
of it. So there's sort of, again, a lot of EDA on steroids that I've seen there. I think that's

00:09:55.039 --> 00:10:04.320
sort of been the general theme. The thing I do not do is I don't do a lot of like ML engineering

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:09.280
type, let's build like a deep neural network kind of data science, which is another flavor of data

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:14.559
science. I've dabbled in it. I dabbled in it occasionally, but as part of my role, I don't

00:10:14.559 --> 00:10:22.640
really do that. Well, speaking of dabbling in things, I love math, but I didn't get to do math

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:29.520
in college. You did pure math, a PhD in pure math. I'm curious about how your transition from

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:36.239
PhD in pure math in Texas happens to data science. Can you talk a little bit about that?

00:10:37.919 --> 00:10:41.280
This is the part where I'm going to make it sound like there was a lot of

00:10:42.559 --> 00:10:46.559
deep thought and planning, and it's actually probably all correlations.

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:55.280
So I started, as you said, as a very, very, very like pure, the purest of pure mathematicians.

00:10:56.159 --> 00:11:02.960
In fact, so pure that I even wrote a book in pure math, like that's how extreme it was.

00:11:04.239 --> 00:11:10.799
And I think it was over time, I think I just sort of happened to run into people,

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:19.679
and I think this is a big part of my experience has been like, you just sort of run into people

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:26.960
who sort of just help you think about things, help you think differently. They sort of shape

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:31.280
your, they shape like your view of the world. And so I was like, down this like very pure math part,

00:11:31.919 --> 00:11:38.960
and I'm like, okay, that's what I'm going to do. And I happened to run into

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:44.880
sort of just a couple of folks, first at Vanderbilt during my postdoc, who were pure math

00:11:44.880 --> 00:11:51.280
folks who were sort of doing more applied math. And I was like, you know, going to their seminars

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:53.359
and just seeing what they're doing, like all this kind of cool stuff, and they're doing sort of

00:11:53.359 --> 00:11:58.320
signal processing and things, which is, again, a form of data science and a form of data analysis,

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:03.280
and you can see applications. And then there was sort of work being done around like compressed

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:08.239
sensing. So there was just like these applications of the things I knew, and that sort of opened my

00:12:08.239 --> 00:12:16.400
eyes like, oh, this stuff, you know, the pure stuff when applied is like really cool. And then

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:23.919
I ended up in an office next to a colleague of mine who was very into topic modeling at that

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:28.640
time, and sort of that kind of like machine learning and data science. And we just started

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:35.280
talking, right? And I think this is where like, I really emphasize to folks that I meet like,

00:12:36.159 --> 00:12:41.760
data science is not about data, it's about the people. It's actually not a profession about data,

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:46.799
it's a profession about people. And we started talking, and I got interested in like this stuff,

00:12:46.799 --> 00:12:52.000
and I was like, this clustering stuff is so cool. And then I started learning some tools. And,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.719
you know, I was fiddling around with pandas, like early versions of pandas, and early versions of

00:12:56.719 --> 00:13:02.000
these things, and just like messing around. I just got into it. I was like, could this just be my job,

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:09.119
right? Like, could I just do this instead? And that's how I sort of ended up as a data scientist.

00:13:09.119 --> 00:13:13.520
And then I think you just sort of take the shortest or the most convenient part you can to

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:22.080
get your goal. And so I was working at the Naval Academy in the math department. And so you can

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:28.400
sort of see like military, then go to USA, which is a company, but very focused on the military.

00:13:29.039 --> 00:13:34.400
And then I was like, what kind of quant do I want to be? Let me like, let me grow up a little bit.

00:13:34.400 --> 00:13:38.799
And I was like, I kind of wanted to investing. And so within USA, I kind of went to the investment

00:13:38.799 --> 00:13:42.880
part of USA. And then I was like, oh, this is really cool. I really like investing and data.

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:46.640
And then I went to BlackRock. And so that's how I ended up with BlackRock. And at BlackRock,

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:53.440
I kind of learned, you know, I really like the technology, and I like the data management,

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:56.799
and I like sifting through the data a lot. And I want to do that at a bigger scale,

00:13:57.359 --> 00:14:04.799
tech company. So that's kind of how I ended up on this journey. I actually had no idea when I

00:14:04.799 --> 00:14:09.679
started. I was like, let's just go that way. Like, I didn't know I was going to be a data

00:14:09.679 --> 00:14:13.760
scientist. I'll just go that way and see what happens. No, I didn't know that I was going to

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:19.280
be either. And I started in, I started as a finance major, personal finance major, and kind

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:23.599
of wandered around until I took a stats class. And I was like, oh, wait, no, that's this is what

00:14:23.599 --> 00:14:29.359
I want to do. I want to do stats, and I want to use computers. Thank you for sharing that. I really

00:14:29.359 --> 00:14:35.520
was kind of wondering if you use any pure math in your day-to-day job. But it sounds like the

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:40.640
shift, even though it's pretty big, has been really beneficial for you. And this kind of ties

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:45.280
into Mike's question. Mike, I saw you had a question in the chat, which is about management.

00:14:45.280 --> 00:14:51.760
Are you available to ask that? Sure. So it was interesting to hear that you've said that you've

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:59.840
done both people management and now tech lead. One question was kind of, if you could give advice

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:04.880
to younger you who's a people manager, or just about to become a people manager, what would you

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:11.119
tell? What would you say? Or, and would you say, yeah, go do the people management, because it's

00:15:11.119 --> 00:15:16.960
a great thing, and you'll learn lots about dealing with people. Or would you say, don't do it, become

00:15:16.960 --> 00:15:25.039
the technical lead? If I could, that's a great question. If I could go back and give my younger

00:15:25.039 --> 00:15:33.599
self some advice, I would say, I would say the advice I'd give myself is, wait as long as you can

00:15:33.599 --> 00:15:40.000
to be a people manager. I think being a people manager was actually a very good experience.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:46.239
I really enjoy being a people manager. I tell people I like the people part of it. I don't

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:52.559
like the management part of it as much, but right, like there's sort of a bureaucratic

00:15:52.559 --> 00:15:56.479
overhead to being a manager, and after a while you're just like, I just don't do this anymore.

00:15:56.479 --> 00:16:04.640
Yeah, I hate to be a manager. I love working with people. And I think in all the roles I was in, I

00:16:04.640 --> 00:16:10.559
think it was a, I think it was a sort of a natural thing where the, where people would tell you like,

00:16:10.559 --> 00:16:18.159
hey, your career progress is very much about like moving from, you know, being an individual

00:16:18.159 --> 00:16:22.640
contributor to being a people manager, and these two things are very like disjoint.

00:16:23.919 --> 00:16:27.119
And so you say, oh, well, okay, that's, that's what I got to do. That's the step.

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:30.400
So I think if I could really go back, I would say like, hey, like,

00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:37.599
figure out how you can make this individual role in any form work for as long as you can,

00:16:38.559 --> 00:16:44.080
and figure out how to do the people part of it more and more without doing the management.

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:50.960
So mentoring, collaborating on projects, you know, working across like a larger organization

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:56.640
is like stakeholder, like there's all these ways you can experience that aspect of like

00:16:56.640 --> 00:17:02.159
working with people and sort of interacting with people. And like, well, even, you know,

00:17:02.159 --> 00:17:07.119
you can do all of that stuff without actually having to do the formal management. That's

00:17:07.599 --> 00:17:11.439
one piece of advice I'd give myself. I guess the other way of putting it is like, don't be in a

00:17:11.439 --> 00:17:18.000
rush, right? Like, don't just be like, the path forward as a data scientist is up this ladder,

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:28.719
which involves write code, manage, right? I would say like, having, I've actually,

00:17:28.719 --> 00:17:33.920
this is the first time, sort of a weird thing in the career, but maybe this is actually the

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:41.520
