00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:04.239
in my case. And I've actually enjoyed it a lot. I've enjoyed just doing my own thing.

00:18:06.800 --> 00:18:09.760
That sounds really, really nice. Mike, any follow ups there?

00:18:10.719 --> 00:18:16.560
Well, yeah, I, I completely echo that sentiment of not rushing into it, because I think if you

00:18:17.199 --> 00:18:25.359
rush into being a manager too soon, then often you wind up being not a very effective manager.

00:18:26.319 --> 00:18:32.000
I, you know, whereas I think if you, if you can get that experience, just as you're saying,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:36.800
get the experience, you know, learn about a lot of things, including yourself,

00:18:37.599 --> 00:18:42.160
then you can be a much more effective manager when it comes. So, yeah.

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:51.359
I also, I also feel like, it's, I think there's an aspect of this, which is, this maybe goes a

00:18:51.439 --> 00:18:55.199
little bit back to like the sort of this notion I have of like the flavors of data science,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:07.520
is data scientists are a very varied bunch of people. It is actually quite hard to say,

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:13.599
go manage 27 data scientists. Like, in many organizations, like it works in some places,

00:19:13.599 --> 00:19:19.199
but it's actually sort of, I think it sort of puts an emphasis a little bit on the fact that

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:24.000
it's a, it's sort of similar, like the sort of variety of data science and actually

00:19:24.880 --> 00:19:28.880
